- {x | p' x} ∈ 𝓝 x
- {x | q x} ∈ 𝓝 x
- {x | q' x} ∈ 𝓝 x

And we need to show:
- {x | p x ∧ q x ∨ p' x ∧ q' x} ∈ 𝓝 x

To prove this, we can use the fact that a set s is in the filter if and only if every point x in s is a limit point of s. Alternatively, we can use the basic properties of filters: if s ∈ F and t ∈ F, then s ∩ t ∈ F, and if s ∈ F and f is continuous at each point of s, then f(s) ∈ F.

In our case, we can observe that:
- {x | p x ∧ q x} = {x | p x} ∩ {x | q x}
- {x | p' x ∧ q' x} = {x | p' x} ∩ {x | q' x}
- The union of these two sets is {x | p x ∧ q x ∨ p' x ∧ q' x}

Since {x | p x} ∈ 𝓝 x and {x | q x} ∈ 𝓝 x, their intersection {x | p x} ∩ {x | q x} is also in 𝓝 x. Similarly, {x | p' x} ∩ {x | q' x} is in 𝓝 x. Then, since both of these sets are in 𝓝 x, their union is also in 𝓝 x.

